00–about 1300","1300–1300":"1300–1300","1211–1311":"1211–1311","1241–1341":"1241–1341","1257–1357":"1257–1357","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1320–1352":"1320–1352","–Male":"Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1352":"1352","1341":"1341","1241":"1241","1270":"1270","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1357":"1357","Abt 1300":"about 1300","1257":"1257","1300":"1300","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1211":"1211","1320":"1320","about 1300":"about 1300","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brickill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one or other of the places called Bricqueville in Normandy, such as Bricqueville-la-Blouette and Bricqueville-sur-Mer (both Manche), and Bricqueville (Calvados).","English: variant of <b>Breakell</b>, a nickname for a destructive person from Middle English <i>breken</i> ‘to break’ + <i>all</i> ‘all, everything’.","Variant of   Brickel  , a surname of German origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Brickle","meanings":["English: variant of   Brickell  .","Variant of   Brickel  , of German origin."]},{"name":"Brickel","meanings":["Americanized form of South German and Swiss German <b>Brückel</b>, <b>Brückl</b>: topographic name for someone who lived by a small bridge, from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>brücke</i> ‘bridge’. Compare   Brickell   and   Brickle  .","South German: nickname perhaps for a stocky, squat person, related to the word <i>Bröckel</i>, a diminutive of <i>Brocken</i> ‘chunk’.","English: variant of   Brickell  ."]},{"name":"Brickles","meanings":["English: variant of   Brickell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Brickill was born about 1300, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir. Hugh Brickill, was 31 and her mother, Jonet Hammond, was 32. She had at least 8 sons and 2 daughters with Ithel Fychan ab Ithel Llwyd. She died about 1300, in her hometown, at the age of 2, and was buried in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1300–Abt 1300":"umbes 1300–umbes 1300","1300–1300":"1300–1300","1211–1311":"1211–1311","1241–1341":"1241–1341","1257–1357":"1257–1357","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1320–1352":"1320–1352","–Male":"Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1352":"1352","1341":"1341","1241":"1241","1270":"1270","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1357":"1357","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1257":"1257","1300":"1300","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1211":"1211","1320":"1320","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1300–Abt 1300":"noin 1300–noin 1300","1300–1300":"1300–1300","1211–1311":"1211–1311","1241–1341":"1241–1341","1257–1357":"1257–1357","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1320–1352":"1320–1352","–Male":"Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1352":"1352","1341":"1341","1241":"1241","1270":"1270","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1357":"1357","Abt 1300":"noin 1300","1257":"1257","1300":"1300","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1211":"1211","1320":"1320","about 1300":"noin 1300","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englant